entry.title: Don't always use current snap ratio to check snappability
entry.content:
This CL fixes the issue that some components use the current snap ratio

to check the snappability even if the to-be-snapped window ends up being

snapped with the default snap ratio.

For example, when a 1/3-partial snapped window is re-snapped via

overview mode, the window gets 1/2-snapped regardless of the previous

snap ratio. So the overview mode should check the snappability with the

default snap ratio instead of the current ratio in that case.



This CL also renames the overloaded `CanSnapWindow` method as

`CanKeepCurrentSnapRatio` to make the condition clear.

entry.title: Use network::ResourceRequest instead of WebURLRequest in ResourceFetcher
entry.content:
blink::WebURLRequest is used for the argument of

URLLoaderThrottleProvider::CreateThrottles() method after [1]. But we

are planing to call this method from the background thread where we

don't use blink::WebURLRequest [2]. Also we are planing to deprecate

blink::WebURLRequest, and planing to use network::ResourceRequest

instead [3].



So this CL changes the argument type of CreateThrottles() from

blink::WebURLRequest to network::ResourceRequest.

A network::ResourceRequest is created in ResourceLoader::Start(). So we

pass the reference of the structure through ResourceFetcher::

CreateURLLoader().



In frames:

ResourceLoader::Start()

-> ResourceFetcher::CreateURLLoader()

-> LoaderFactoryForFrame::CreateURLLoader()

|-> URLLoaderThrottleProvider::CreateThrottles()

|-> ServiceWorkerNetworkProviderForFrame::

| GetSubresourceLoaderFactory()

|-> URLLoaderFactory::CreateURLLoader()



In workers:

ResourceLoader::Start()

-> ResourceFetcher::CreateURLLoader()

-> LoaderFactoryForWorker::CreateURLLoader()

|-> WebWorkerFetchContext::CreateThrottles()

| -> WebServiceWorkerFetchContextImpl::CreateThrottles() or

| DedicatedOrSharedWorkerFetchContextImpl::CreateThrottles()

| -> URLLoaderThrottleProvider::CreateThrottles()

|-> URLLoaderFactory::CreateURLLoader()



mojom::blink::RequestContextType in blink::WebURLRequest is checked in

the code path. But this type member is not in network::ResourceRequest.

network::ResourceRequest has a network::mojom::RequestDestination

member. And some of these checks of mojom::blink::RequestContextType can

be safely converted to network::mojom::RequestDestination without any

behavior change. But the check in ResourceFetcher::CreateURLLoader()

needs the mojom::blink::RequestContextType. Also we need to pass

`service_worker_race_network_request_token` to

LoaderFactoryForWorker::CreateURLLoader(), and

`is_from_origin_dirty_style_sheet` flag to

ServiceWorkerNetworkProviderForFrame::GetSubresourceLoaderFactory().

So this CL adds these three arguments to CreateURLLoader() methods.



[1]: https://crrev.com/c/994152

[2]: https://crrev.com/c/5113665

[3]: https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/forum/#!topic/platform-architecture-dev/ntSzerId4gw

entry.title: Fork Lacros's zygote processes at login screen (under flag)
entry.content:
This change introduces a feature flag `kLacrosForkZygotesAtLoginScreen`

which moves the WaitForLogin barrier further down the Lacros

initialization process. Importantly, because no accesses to the

cryptohome are now performed before this point, Lacros can fork

the Zygote processes at login screen.



When this flag is enabled, it can save up to additional ~1.13s of

Lacros startup time on low-end devices such as Grunt

(see go/lacros-loginscreen-cryptohome for details),

compared to the initial implementation of prelaunching.

entry.title: [omnibox] Fix dangling `raw_ptr` in history fuzzy provider
entry.content:
crrev.com/c/5153332 changed `AutocompleteMatch::provider` from a

standard raw ptr (`AutocompleteProvider*`) to a chromium raw ptr

(`raw_ptr`). This exposed a dangling raw ptr case

in the history fuzzy provider that reproduced 100% of the time.



Before,

1. `HistoryFuzzyProvider::Start()` would call `DoAutocomplete()`.

2. `DoAutocomplete()` would create history quick and bookmark providers

3. The matches generated by those temporary providers would have their

`provider` field set to those temporary providers.

4. `Start()` would overwrite the matches' providers to point to the

fuzzy provider. However, the temporary history quick and bookmark

providers were out of scope in `Start()`, so `Start()` would be

overwriting dangling pointers.



This CL fixes this by moving the provider overwriting (step 4) from

`Start()` to `AddConvertedMatches()`, which is called from

`DoAutocomplete()`, so the proivders are still in scope. This also makes

more semantic sense.



Bug: 1446392

entry.title: Reland "Remove and simplify UI after VRB removal"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 4ec416a0dd6fe984ae5456311e2db03f059a888e



Original change's description:

> Remove and simplify UI after VRB removal

>

> After the VR Browser removal, there are a number of interfaces that

> had only a single implementation outside of testing, often with that

> implementation being either solely a no-op or having some additional

> complexity in order to support splitting the code into these interfaces.

> One of the most complex things that was now only enabled in tests was

> the `gvr_input_support` bool which enabled a lot of input infrastructure

> which is now not processed at all, thus enabling a lot of cleanups. This

> change thus removes the input infrastructure and the no-op interface

> methods. The most interesting removal caused by the removal of this UI

> infrastructure is that kWebVrExclusiveScreenToast could no longer be

> made visible from production code, but it could (and it's visibility

> was checked) from test code. While tests were modified because of this,

> it does not appear that any valid scenarios are now tested less.

>

> Two interface methods had some slightly complex behavior which was

> instead simplified:

> SchedulerDelegate's OnPose method was called by the

> `VrBrowserRendererThreadWin` to call a method onto the `BrowserRenderer`

> which then made a callback to the `SchedulerDelegate` who triggered a

> callback that it received from the `VrBrowserRendererThreadWin`, all on

> the same thread. This circler dependency was simplified to have

> `VrBrowserRendererThreadWin` both call `BrowserRenderer` directly (since

> it already owned it), and to call it's own follow-up method after an

> appropriate call was made.

>

> BrowserRendererBrowserInterface was now only used by tests to be

> notified when the visibility state of a requested UI had been changed,

> and it could only listen for the visibility state changes of one piece

> of UI at a time. Thus the BrowserRendererBrowserInterface was removed

> and replaced with a simple `OnceCallback` on the struct that was passed

> in to set up the wait for a visibility state change. This struct was

> also simplified as two different structs existed; one which was created

> by the tests and one which was created by the product code, with only

> very minimal differences that could easily be adapted.

>

> Other noteworthy interface changes are:

> SchedulerBrowserRendererInterface now only had one implementation and

> the interface itself wasn't actually used (except for the fact that

> the interface made it's methods public and the implementation had them

> private), since the only place that used the interface directly created

> the BrowserRenderer which implemented the interface thus it was removed.

>

> UiBrowserInterface had only a single remaining method which was a noop,

> so it was removed.

>

> A few minor changes were made:

> Floor Height was never set, and so it was removed and its usage

> simplified.

>

> TransparentQuadRenderer was effectively unused since it was impossible

> for DrawTexturedQuad to be passed an invalid texture.

>

> Some UiCreation exports/indirections were created for the VR DFM and are

> thus no longer needed.

>

> `PerformActionAndWaitForVisibilityStatus` didn't actually perform the

> passed in action and all callers were passing `Base::DoNothing` anyway,

> so the method was renamed to `WaitForVisibilityStatus` and the action

> param was removed.

>

> A few removals happened because they were either now or previously no

> longer referenced:

> Some strings

> chrome/browser/vr/vector_icons

> Backplanes Draw Phase

> Element Names/Friendly Names

> Various values and enums in `ui_test_input`

The initial grid-area support relied only on implicit line names,

and not the named grid area map, which is used to generate implicit

line names. This worked for layout, but devtools relies on the named

grid area map.

instead merge the named area map, and then regenerates implicit lines

based on the merged map. This approach works in both devtools and

layout. This approach also removed a bunch of TODO's in the old

version.

entry.title: Update FrameSequenceTrackerV3 to handle late arriving frames
entry.content:
Currently FrameSequenceTrackers are destroyed in response to a frame

submission that occurs after the last one being measured for the legacy

V1 sequence. This however can occur before we have received the

PresentationFeedback for the frame we are measuring.



This results in the traces for FrameSequenceTrackerV3 terminating

without the nested trace for that final frame.



This change updates FrameSequenceTracker to use the V3 FrameSorter path

to terminate itself. Allowing the trace to have the appropriate end

point.





We have also moved some tests to be ChromeOS only, as they utilize

ui::ThroughputTracker. This is only setup and using V3 on ChromeOS. So

the tests no longer work without the V1 path on other platforms. And

are pointless on them anyways.

and setting the transitionary opacity in the state instead of the

quad.

entry.title: [Read Aloud] Workaround for bug where colors don't always load.
entry.content:
For some reason (likely because Reading Mode is untrusted), color tokens

don't load sometimes first launch. Colors remain unloaded until a new

tab is opened and Reading Mode is reopened.



When this happens, everything looks very broken because none of our

colors work, so this workaround uses color tokens defined in app.ts

only when in the buggy state. The colors defined in app.ts are

redefinitions of colors in chrome/browser/ui/color/chrome_color_id.h.



The Views toolbar wasn't impacted by this bug because the colors were

loaded from the UntrustedPageHandler, outside of the untrusted

TypeScript.



This bug happens extremely frequently on first launch (such as when

rebuilding Chrome or relaunching after a feature flag change), but

doesn't happen after the new tab has been opened. Once the stylesheet

has been loaded the first time, closing and reopening Chrome usually

doesn't trigger any need to reload the stylesheets, so the workaround

won't be needed in the majority of cases.



See b/293464821#comment4 or crbug.com/1516972
